------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT THIS IS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Jacobian lens (jlens): companion reference implementation for
"Verbalizable Representations Form a Global Workspace in Language Models"
(Gurnee et al. 2026, https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/workspace/index.html).

It reads out what an internal decoder-transformer activation is *disposed to make
the model say*: it transports a residual-stream vector at any layer/position into
the final-layer basis with an averaged input-output Jacobian, then decodes it
through the model's unembedding into a ranked list of vocabulary tokens.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHY VENDORED (path a: literal upstream source, pinned)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Upstream states plainly: "Reference implementation. Not maintained and not
accepting contributions." So it is vendored at the pinned commit above rather
than taken as a package dependency — there will be no upstream releases to track,
and pinning fixes the exact code our results were produced with.

The literal upstream `jlens/` package is vendored verbatim (path a), unlike the
DreamerV3 case (path b, a re-implementation): jlens depends only on torch +
HuggingFace transformers/tokenizers, which KAINE already has via the [training]
extras, so the source imports standalone with no research-harness baggage.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HOW KAINE USES IT
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Offline, build/research-time ONLY. No runtime module under `kaine/` imports
jlens (enforced by keeping all jlens-touching code under `scripts/` and this
`external/` tree). See:

  * openspec/changes/mechanistic-abliteration-lens/  — the design + spec.
  * scripts/abliteration_lens.py                     — the analysis entrypoint.

The tool fits a Jacobian lens on the abliterated organ and compares the vanilla
base vs the abliterated model layer by layer, so a residual or relocated refusal
disposition is visible even when the behavioral abliteration gate passes. The
lens is an averaged-Jacobian approximation and an interpretive signal — it
corroborates the behavioral gate, it does not prove complete refusal removal.

